data.content:
Your test works but has weak assertions — every failure says "Assert.IsTrue failed" with no context. MSTest has `CollectionAssert` and specific asserts for this:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert exact count with a clear failure message
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Assert all items satisfy a condition
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Assert a specific item exists
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, users.Count)` | Failure shows actual count |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)` | Failure shows `Expected:3 Actual:5` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Clearer intent and message |

**Other `CollectionAssert` methods worth knowing:**

- `CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, element)` — item exists
- `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same items, same order
- `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — same items, any order
- `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(collection)` — no duplicates
- `CollectionAssert.IsSubsetOf(subset, superset)` — containment check

**MSTest v3+** also supports `Assert.ThrowsExactly`, `Assert.That.IsNotNull()`, and if you're on **v4**, `Assert.Equals<T>` with better generic support.

For complex collection assertions beyond what `CollectionAssert` offers, consider adding **FluentAssertions** (`users.Should().OnlyContain(u => u.IsActive)`), which gives the richest diagnostics.
